ref=3D"https://scotchaddict.com/author/admin" title=3D"View all posts by Ji=
m" rel=3D"author">Jim</a></span></span>		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class=3D"entry-content">
		<p></p><center><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"http://farm1.static.flickr.=
com/227/500932320_0bd772bf77.jpg" alt=3D"Macallan Barrels"></center><br>
One of the best parts of the Macallan tour was the special barrel/art of co=
opering section they had above the warehouse. In it, they explained the dif=
ference between American oak and French oak, barrel construction, and other=
 aspects of coopering.<p></p>
<p>Did you know that a barrel has a standard volume of 36 Imperial gallons?=
 (43 US gallons) </p>
<p>I didn=E2=80=99t, I figured barrel was a general term for a container of=
 that general size and shape. Well, to make things more interesting, there =
are actually many varying sizes of =E2=80=9Cbarrels,=E2=80=9D some of which=
 have very funny names (all gallons are Imperial gallons):</p>
<ul>
<li>Firkin =E2=80=93 9 gallons</li>
<li>Kilderkin =E2=80=93 18 gallons</li>
<li>Barrel =E2=80=93 36 gallons</li>
<li>Hogshead =E2=80=93 54 gallons</li>
<li>Butt =E2=80=93 108 gallons</li>
<li>Tun =E2=80=93 216 gallons</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Firkin</strong> =E2=80=93 It=E2=80=99s an old English term deriv=
ed from a Middle Dutch word <em>vierdekijn</em>, which means fourth. It=E2=
=80=99s appropriate because a firkin is a fourth of a barrel in volume.</p>
<p><strong>Kilderkin</strong> =E2=80=93 Again an old English term derived f=
rom Dutch but it doesn=E2=80=99t mean half, it just means small cask, but i=
t is a half barrel.</p>
<p><strong>Hogshead</strong> =E2=80=93 I wasn=E2=80=99t able to find the or=
igin of the term but it was standardized as 54 gallons by an act of Parliam=
ent in 1423.</p>
<p><strong>Butt</strong> =E2=80=93 This size in wine is called a <strong>pi=
pe</strong>, so when The Balvenie Portwood Finish 21 states it was finished=
 in Port pipes, it means barrels of this size.</p>
<p><strong>Tun</strong> =E2=80=93 It sounds like ton because it shares the =
same origin though the latter refers only to mass/weight.</p>
<p><strong>Finally, what=E2=80=99s the difference between Imperial gallons =
and US gallons?</strong> The US measurement comes from the English measurem=
ents of the Middle Ages, it wasn=E2=80=99t until 1824 that the English deri=
ved the Imperial system, which was after American independence. An Imperial=
 gallon works out to be a little over 1.2 US gallons (technically, ~1.20094=
992550 US gallons).</p>
<p>It=E2=80=99s always interesting to learn a little bit of trivia!</p>
<p><em>(Photo: <a href=3D"http://www.flickr.com/photos/schlaeger/500932320/=
sizes/m/">schlaeger</a>)</em></p>
